segments.text: know that I was leaving him there because he was going through.
I left him alongside the road.
I pulled him into a nice parking area where he wouldn't get run over by somebody, but as far as I know, he may not have ever made it to Sonora.
But had several good experiences.
In fact, I've had people go out of their way as far as 30 or 40 miles to take you further along to where you could pick up a ride or
get you closer to home.
If somebody was going through there, going to Junction, or wasn't going to Junction, they'd be going to someplace like Menard.
It was only 30 miles away.
I was running you over there.
And we'll do that.
It'll be a very nice fun day.
I have not yet had anybody share a truly bad Aggie hitchhiking experience.
In other words, a number like you, they were drinking too much, driving too fast, but nothing worse than that.
No, I never had a real bad experience, not having any sort of a threatening problem with anyone.
Describe, after being in the service for those years, describe having to buckle down to study.
What was it like that first fall?
Scared to death.
First place, nearly all of us,
had been out of school or had never either been to school or had been out for a long time.
But most of the ones that I all knew, none of them had ever been to college before.
They'd been out.
They knew that they were behind in terms of their peer groups.
These kids that they'd graduated from high school with and went on to college were already juniors or seniors or maybe some of them already out of school.
So we were older, although
I was still not all that old at that time, but it was very serious.
You studied and we were not really greatly appreciated by the rest of the student body because we raised the curve.
We did make much better grades.
And really the first year I was here,
Of course, everybody here was Corps.
They really didn't know what to do with us.
They didn't know how to treat us.

Here we were, we'd been in the military, had been in service, and most of us had been in combat before, and they were just trying to get in it, and they had their own sets of rules and protocols and the systems that they had grown up with or had developed here.
So we were sort of an anomaly for them.
for the rest of the student body, particularly the upperclassmen.
Did any of the Corps come out there the first fall to try to teach y'all Aggie myths and legends and all that?
They did originally.
They didn't last very long.
They didn't do it.
They found out that we were not really, as a group, all that interested in
raw, raw part of going to school, of the university life, that we were primarily interested in getting our studies done, getting our grades done, getting, progressing on through and getting out.
Alright, did y'all come into football games?
Yeah.
Describe your first, if you remember, what it was like to go to an Aggie football game that fall.
One thing they did do, they convinced me that A&M was invisible, invincible in football, and I was greatly shocked to find out how
Badly, I was misled.
I think in my four years at A&M, we won a total of eight ballgames.
But every weekend, every week, we was darn sure we were going to be here when we were playing that week.
You know, one of the things Bernie Welch told me that helps explain that,
and he very very proud and grateful to coach norton he said coach norton promised every single person that had played for him if you serve on active duty you have a scholarship
And he said, when we came back, we weren't nearly as good athletes and we weren't ready to concentrate on that.
We had, you know, we were more serious now.
But he honored that commitment and he said, as a result, we didn't win many games and he lost his job.
Yeah.
Well, I saw Barney Wells score the first touchdown at the University of Texas.
We went to that game every year as well.
Even when they played it in San Antonio.
So that...
Now, when y'all went to the game, did you sit as a group, you veterans?
Generally did, because we all had tickets in the same general.
Did y'all stand up like all the other students?
Oh, yeah.
Okay, so you did.
And did the L's.
Did the L's, yeah.
They taught us that.
But you would have been the only civilian freshman and sophomore students, wouldn't you?
In other words, the only ones not in uniform.
Not in uniform.
They had a few what they called day dodgers that were in the regular corps but did not participate in anything but the drills.
As far as you can recall, who was running the vet outfit?
Who was in charge, do you know?
On site control, I really don't remember.
As I recall, Tom Harrington had as much to do with it as anyone, but he wasn't out there all the time.
Of course, he was in here most of the time.
Did you have anybody that you as an individual turned to for advice out there?
How did you know what courses to take?
That's a good question.
you sort of had the catalog and decided what it was that you thought you needed and just sort of went in and signed up for those courses.
There wasn't a whole lot of guidance in terms of curriculum in terms of for future until well we got we got in here on back in here on campus then the next year and then we got more involved.
Did you have any social life in those days?
I did.
Dated
A couple of girls that, of course, none of them local.
Again, having to hitchhike to San Marcos to talk.
T.W.
and my wife, who I later married, was going to the University of Texas at the time.
Now, when do you meet her?
In the end of my junior year.
Oh, so that's later.
And then you go home, Thanksgiving, Christmas.
Thanksgiving, Christmas.
Do you remember giving your family or anybody there any description of what it was like?
What were you telling them A&M was?
Well, of course, I was real proud to be going to A&M, to go to any school, but particularly A&M, and we were

Of course, we had a ranch and a farm, and my dad was always interested in the new developments in agriculture and the new types of grasses that we might grow that would do better in that darn rocky hill country than what we already had up there.
Of course, what we really needed to do was take about half the stock off of it for a few years, but we didn't think we could afford to do that.
But A&M was quite respected.
in our rural part of the world.
I don't know why I had not heard more about A&M before I went in to the Marine Corps.
And you never thought about dropping out?
No.
So you're, all right, and you come back then the spring semester, things go well.
Yeah.
Did your grades both, the first two semesters, were those were good?
Good grades.
I made, uh,
Well, we were on the three-point system then, so I was about a 2.7 and doing well.
And did you zero in on economics in the spring?
No, I didn't do that until I got back in on campus, and then I decided that, in fact, it was ag economics that I went into and never regretted doing it.
It was a very broad-based course, curriculum, and gave you a lot of insight into it.
a whole bunch of things that I don't think I would have gotten.
I got very interested in things like geology and just fascinating.
Paleontology, I wish I could be a paleontologist.
That would be great.
I don't think I could make a living doing that.
All right, so you're out there all year, and then you go home for the summer?
I went home for the summer, worked in the summer, every summer.
Doing what?
Well, I either worked the first summer, I worked on our range and various ranges.
And then on the second one, the second summer, and the third, let's see, the second summer, I worked for Exxon, or Umbalo at that time.

They had, at that time, all of their pipeline operations were staffed at service points, and I was, I spent the summer out between Sonora and El Dorado at what they called Station A, where they had a, you lived out there, they had a crew, a five-person crew with
enough people to be sure there was 24-hour coverage on everything.
And good experience.
They had one provision I thought was real odd in their requirement.
They'd be happy to hire anybody going to school that they could place, but you had to agree that you would not come back as a full employee.
That this was, you were purely a temporary employee for the summer.
And when the summer was over, you had to go back to school.
And you had to agree to do that before they'd hire you.
All right, so you came back here then your sophomore year.
Yeah.
And on the campus, main campus?
On the main campus, up on the dorm next to the dormitory.
All right, describe that routine for an old veteran.
An old veteran, again, that's where we really got most of our interface with the existing student body.
because now we were in with them all the time.
And while there was some getting used to of each other, it never really, as far as I could tell, there was never any real problem with it.
I think probably, let's get another up to the next year, when it joined the Corps the next year, and we had our own outfit.
We had our own, what do they call it, the wing.
with their own structure in it.

There was a little friction then between the younger members of our group, the sophomores and freshmen that had come in to the Corps there, and the regular seniors and juniors in the regular Corps, because we didn't think we needed to snap two every time we saw one of them and that sort of thing.
But that got worked out.
That got worked out pretty well.
Wait, still on that second year, your sophomore year, was there a good retention rate of those who had been freshmen out at Bryan Field?

Not as good as I would have thought there would have been, because for several reasons, I think, and not just because of grades, although we did have a few that just were not capable of doing the work.
did not make it past that first year.
But we also had those that figured they were already too far behind.
They needed to get married and settle down.
Some of them, you know, up in their mid-20s that decided it was time to go out and try to earn a living and support their wife and get married and have a family.
So we lost a few that way.
But I'd say the losses were not as great as they were
in the regular population of the school.
Looking back on that year, was that, given the realities they had to deal with, was that a good solution to the situation?
Had lots of veterans, couldn't build the housing that quickly?
I don't think, I think they did the best thing they could do.
I think that the Bryan Air Force Base, while we bitched about it, and moving out there,
was better than most of us had come from.
I'd lived in a pup tent for a whole lot of months that were a whole lot worse than that.
And while it was not as what I was looking forward to, it was not bad at all.
It really wasn't bad.
All right.
Now, then here on the campus, your sophomore year, you lived where?
I think at dorm 17.
And I had a brother.
by the way, at that time, who had come out of the, he had been on the Signal Corps, Pat, I don't know if you remember Pat.
He was head of the Real Estate Research Center.
Oh, yes.
And he and I shared a room one year, that sophomore year.
And you were still referred to as vets.
Yep.
And you wore civilian clothes to class.
Right.
What was, what did a typical undergraduate male wear then?
What were, what was normal Aggie clothing?
Blue jeans.
or khaki pants and a sports shirt of some type.
Those of us who came from out in rural countries generally had a denim jacket that we wore.
What kind of foot gear?
Boots.
Not cowboy boots, though?
Yeah.
Oh, they were?
Yeah.
I was going to get work boots.
Well, we also had those, the cowboy boots, too, because most of you out there grew up with cowboy boots on the high-top boots.
Did you wear a hat at all during the day?
I would have never really been a big hat wearer.
Most people did wear hats, but I did not wear a hat.
How was the routine in the classroom here compared to what it had been out there at Bryan Field?
Of course it was a little easier to get to classes here because you knew where things were.
The professors here were more oriented at what they were doing and the way they were doing it here.
So they were probably less flexibility in dealing with the student population that they had than we had out there.
But overall,
I think it, I think we transformed pretty well into the general student body here.
We became, we were not considered to be a big anomaly as far as the student body was concerned.
We were vets, they still complained about, we were running the curves on all the classes and that sort of thing, but
But not in a bitter way.
Now, did a freshman whip out to you vets?
He would when we were in the Corps.
No, but when you were a sophomore, did anybody expect y'all to go to Yale practice that sophomore year?
No, you went to the...
silver taps and things like that, but you could go to Yale practice if you wanted to, but it wasn't a requirement.
Silver taps was not held out at Bryan Field, or was it?
No.
So here.
Do you remember your impression of silver taps when you first?
Very impressed with it, and still am.
I still, that just sends cold chills down my back every time I hear that.
Do you think it was more meaningful to you and your fellow veterans than it would have been to the non-veterans?
I think so.
I think it was.
We'd heard it for real a lot of times.
It was always a very impressive thing.
Okay, now I want to really hope you have some thoughts about Bonfire.
This would have been the fall of 47.
describe Bonfire that year, as far as you remember, your first year on campus?
I'm not sure whether it was that year or the next year that we got it bombed.
Do you remember that?
I've heard about it.
But it was on the, Bonfire was on the drill field.
On the drill field.
And it was nothing like the Bonfire now in structure.
But it was all logs.
All logs.
And it was TPed up.
Just like this.
And about how long did they work on it?
Seemed to be like maybe two or three weeks.
It was not the long period of time that they spend on it now.
My grandson just graduated.
They spent a lot of time cutting and hauling.
So one of the things I haven't been able to get much information on yet
is apparently before the war it was all just trash and clutter.
And how did it suddenly become logs?
I haven't found anybody with any know-how on that yet.
I don't know how it changed.
I think it was logs the first time that we were involved in it here.
Oh, I think 46 even it may have been logs.
Do you remember whether y'all came in for bonfire or not from out at the base?
Yeah, we did.
It was logs?
I think it was logs, the best I can recall.
And I know it was when I was in here about 47 and 48, because then we were, even though that's when I was in the Corps, and we were guarding it, and we were guarding the bonfire.
You know, they're hard enough to set a fire with all that diesel fuel on them, but we guarded it, and we had it bombed one year.
Yeah, describe that.
I wasn't out there at the time, but...
Two kids from UT flew over in a small airplane and dropped some, what do you call it, Molotov cocktail things, a gallon jug of gasoline with a wick in it.
And they were so enthralled in dropping that on the stack of logs that we had up there that they grounded right out on the other side of the airport out there.
But it caused great excitement.
Oh, everybody couldn't believe, you know, that they were trying to burn our bonfire.
Did you guys, did any Aggie students get to them after they grounded?
I don't think so.
I don't think we even knew that they had grounded until way after that.
I think they...
Were they able to take it off and then... Well, I think what they were doing, they weren't paying attention.
They were looking back to see if they really set it afire and just almost flew it into the ground.
And it didn't kill either one of them, no.
Of course, I know it didn't hurt anyone, but it was a good story in a way.
All right.
Here on the campus now, as a non-core member sophomore, what was your routine for a typical class day?
Generally up and have breakfast early.
I always try to schedule early classes.
And then I had to study during the day, too.
Where did you study?
Studying primarily in my room.
Again, in the sophomore year we were over there and nearly all the veterans in that area over there and everybody sort of followed the same procedure.
You studied when you got a chance to during the day.
Then we probably had a little more nightlife then than we had out there because it was a little easier to get together and go out to someplace and have a cold beverage.
Was there much going on at Northgate in those nights then?
Not nearly like it is now.
Northgate was sort of, in fact, Northgate was pretty trashy at that time.
Was the movie theater even there?
Yeah, the movie theater was there.
And the photo outfit was there.
Then you go to Gine Hall.
Yeah, at Gine Hall.
At that time, the name of the building where they had the board's quarters,
And you ate in Sabeasa.
What was your impression of Aggie food?
Good.
Now I thought our food at A&M was
Did you veterans pick up Aggie slang for food and all that?
Yeah, we finally did, yeah.
You finally had to if you were eating a mess all morning.
And I'm assuming that y'all didn't have any pranks in your dorm.
Not much, not much.
Not like they had over, of course, the jocks, the cavalry groups over there, they always had something going on.
But in our dorms, it was pretty quiet.
They didn't have just a whole lot of... No, it was an all-civilian dorm.
Yeah.
By that time, who were the, as far as you were aware, who were the key campus administrators?
Who was running things?
Jim Gilchrist was the chancellor.
President and then chancellor.
Of course, the class of 46, I mean, the class of 50 was such a big class.
Let's say the biggest one we'd ever had for some ten years after that was still the biggest class they'd had here.
But I can't really remember what the rules were that had come down that a number of the Corps leadership had objected to, and they had a march on
Mr. Gilchrist's house.
Did you, by chance, were you present to observe?
I was not.
Didn't even know what was going on until it was over with.
But I then, of course, heard that they had it.
As I understand it, it was, and he was telling them, no more hazing after Thanksgiving, period.
That's it.
That's probably what it was.
And then they marched on his house and turned in their resignations, and he accepted their resignation.
Shocked them.
Yes, and as I understand it, he also told them that if we have any more hazing, then he would not sign for anybody a recommendation that they be commissioned.
I think that was what was really the thing that brought them to it.
Did you as an undergraduate see much of President Gilchrist?
Not really.
I got to know him quite well after I got back here, but I did not really see him.
I saw Dr. Harrington more than I did Mr. Gilchrist.
What was your impression of Dr. Harrington in those days?
I thought he was a very impressive fellow, well-spoken, made a very good impression, handled himself very well.
As far as his philosophy and politics and that sort of thing, I wasn't
a very good judge, but I was quite impressed with him.
Now you, and you, had you gotten into your major for sure by this time?
Sophomore year.
Sophomore year?
Yeah.
And it ended up being ag economics.
Who did you turn to, who were the key people for you on the faculty in economics?
Tyrus Tim,
who became head of the department during that period.
Did you have any courses with him?
Yes, I did.
Describe him as a teacher for us.
He was a good teacher.
He brought in a lot of external information that you did not normally get in a classroom because he'd come out with an extension background, as you probably know,
had a good feel for the people that we were trying to deal with and help.
Now, the head of the department at that time was Mr. L.P. Gabbard, a very fine gentleman.
I knew him better as a graduate student, but he was also a very impressive fellow.
Were there student nicknames for either of them, like there were for many other faculty?
No.
Not for either of them that I can recall.
Who did you turn to for advice about your major?
Primarily John McNeely.
Do you remember John McNeely?
Describe him.
John was a good old South Dakota boy who swore if he ever went back to South Dakota, he wanted to have somebody put him in an institution somewhere.
But he was a livestock marketing man.
I worked with him for years.
He was my major professor.
And very, very considerate, a very effective teacher, I thought, and one that was well liked by the students that he taught.
And I think well respected within the department and within his field.
He had done a lot of research work, and he was my major professor in both my master's and Ph.D. programs.
Can you remember any examples of very important advice that he gave you?
Primarily, Haskell, John worked on the principle that progress was not necessarily made by the smartest people in the world.
It was made by the people that worked hard and studied and kept trying to get it done.
And if you had a problem, you got that problem resolved and moved on to the next one.

I think that was about the most useful kind of direction and advice that I got from him, was that you're not always going to solve the problem the first time you run into it, but the time you work it over a few times, you've got a much better chance of moving forward with it.
What did you think, sophomore, junior year or so, what did you think you were going to do professionally?
I thought I might go into the academic world on the one hand.
I'd had an opportunity to go manage a large ranch up in Virginia, of all places.
I had a Roanoke, Virginia, a horse ranch that was very attractive to me until I thought about it again and again.
But I decided that I would really like to
get involved more in research.
And of course, at that time, basically all economic research was really done in the ag-eco field.

The new developments really came out of the ag-eco work, primarily, as opposed to the pure economics, who were primarily interested in theoretical economics as opposed to the problem-solving types of work.
Were there any other faculty members that were in your undergraduate days that were key to your future as you now realize it?
McNeely was probably the most key particular one.
A fellow named Bob Halpin, H-A-L-P-I-N, who has been gone for several years.
I'm sure he's dead, but now he moved off here probably 20 years ago.
But he was also a very good mentor.
He took time to work with students.
If necessary, he'd do it at night.
He'd invite you out to his house to work on a particular problem that you might have.
He was also a very good influence, I think.
on me but on others that were in the department.
All right and now then as a junior
You decided to be in the Corps.
Saturday I was going to get a commission.
Why?
Oh, that was that commission.
Yeah, I wanted the commission.
That was the thing.
Were your status in the Corps, you were academically a junior, what was your status in the Corps?
Junior.
You were junior, okay.
Junior privileges, all of that sort of thing.
So you didn't have to go through all that fish baloney.
Were you then assigned to a unit?
that had freshmen and sophomores and juniors and seniors that had been through the, were you veterans scattered out?
No.
We were all in the, the units were all veteran.
Ah.
So it was a vet unit.
E-Vet was my company.
And we had a vet wing.
